tr.th: Conclusion and Recommendations based on this report and previous findings known to us

tr.td: The patient shows mildly elevated creatinine and potassium, and low total CO₂, suggesting possible mild renal impairment and metabolic acidosis. Urinalysis reveals glucosuria, ketonuria, bilirubinuria, low specific gravity, and abnormal urine color/appearance, but no infection markers. HbA1c is low, arguing against chronic hyperglycemia. Findings may indicate acute metabolic disturbance (e.g., starvation, dehydration, or renal dysfunction) rather than diabetes. Clinical correlation and further renal and metabolic assessment are recommended.
